<br>
Aye, I looked over the diagram again and indeed the bomber doesn't actually go into orbit.  Not sure how it popped into my head that it did, must be wishful thinking.  That other bomber you mentioned though is menacing on second look.  If the Germans had been able to develop that plane and do it early enough, I imagine it would have flown over American cities with the same ease that B-52s fly over Iraq right now.  With no guided SAMs or jets to intercept it, we'd be sitting ducks.  Actually I think the Germans did develop a jet powered bomber near the end of the war that could outrun any prop-driven fighter but lucky for us it came a tad too late to be of any use. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theredcomin>theredcomin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/5/03 4:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the Germans had won WWII?</span><hr size=1> Quote:<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
England's Fighter force was inferior to the German's during the Battle of Britain... the main reason that Britain was the victor was it's use of RADAR... they could launch intercept squadrons well in advance of the arriving bomber force and have an altitude advantage. This allowed Britain to make the best use of a small air force combating a much larger German Luftwaffe.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Yes, radar was important, but then the Germans had radar too. The difference was that the British had realized its significance  much earlier than the Germans and had developed the Chain Home radar warning system just in time to enable then to track German raids and direct their own aircraft to intercept when the time came.<br>
<br>
As well as that, Britain had increasingly more fighter aircraft than the Luftwaffe. Total German aircraft production in 1940 was 10,826 but the British produced 15,049. This does not include the ever-growing numbers being built under contract for Britain in Canada and the United States. The problem was not lack of planes, but lack of pilots.<br>
<br>
Fortunately, because most of the combat took place over England, RAF pilots who were shot down had a much higher probability of getting back in the air than Luftwaffe pilots, who tended to end up as POWs at best. This geographical bias in favor of the British helped in another way too, as German fighters were limited to only a few minutes over England before they ran out of sufficient fuel to return to base.<br>
<br>
As for the RAF’s fighter force being inferior to the Luftwaffe’s, perhaps you can explain why, during a meeting with Luftwaffe top brass to review what was going wrong in the battle, Göring asked General Adolf Galland if there was anything he could give the Luftwaffe that would really help, Galland said, “Yes. Spitfires.”<br>
<br>
The Messerschmitt Bf 109 was generally accepted as slightly superior to the Hurricane but clearly inferior to the Spitfire when it came to a dogfight, and indeed at the start of 1940 the RAF had more Hurricanes than Spitfires, but as Spitfire production ramped up, there were about four Spitfires in service for every Hurricane by the end of the year.<br>
<br>
By the time the battle began in earnest, the British fighter force was clearly superior to the German one.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
It wouldn't be a question of range... more like could it penetrate a fortified Europe where Luftwaffe jets controlled the skies? Perhaps the 'stealthier' B-49 would be a better choice?<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
In an alternative future where Germany’s mastery over the European mainland seemed settled, it’s improbable that the Luftwaffe would have had any jets worth mentioning. This refers to a more general point I’ll address below. And anyway I suspect a solitary B-29 would not have had so much trouble getting through, especially if a diversionary raid of, say, a couple of hundred were keeping the Luftwaffe busy elsewhere over the Fatherland. <br>
<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
No, they probably couldn't have in our real historical timeline... but in an alternative timeline where WWII lasts much longer, with a German controlled Europe... with the detonations of the US nukes on Japan as proof that it can be built, then perhaps the Germans may have yet developed the 'bomb' a few short years later... maybe by 1948...?<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Here we come to the central point I think has not but should be made in this discussion. <br>
<br>
From everything we know about the way the Nazi state was run and in particular, the way Hitler made decisions, I would strongly suggest that in a hypothetical Germany that had won or was coasting towards winning the war, neither German atomic bombs, jet interceptors, or even such relatively modest rockets as the A4/V2 (when compared with the A9/A10) would ever have seen the light of day.<br>
<br>
Hitler always expected to fight a short war. He was not interested in developing fancy new weapons until about 1943, when it had became clear even to him that victory was not just round the corner—and he began to panic. But if he had been fighting a much longer but more leisurely war that he actually did, then he would not have panicked, but just continued along his apparently successful path.<br>
<br>
Until that change of view in 1943, projects like the A4/V2 pottered along on a relative shoestring, and probably would have continued to do so for many years. However von Braun and company were given essentially an unlimited budget by Speer and then placed under the control of the SS. Even then, the reason it was ever given the go-ahead was von Braun’s assurance to Hitler in early 1943 that they would have a reliable system ready for full-scale use within 12 months. (He delivered very late, and over budget, by the way.)<br>
<br>
Here is the contrast with the German atomic project. Heisenberg persuaded Speer that it would take many years to have a bomb, if it could be made to work at all. That was of no interest to Nazis in a hurry (as they were in real life by this time) and of even less interest to Nazis who could see no use for the thing if they had already won the war; and in any case, the whole atomic project was based upon Jewish, and therefore highly suspect, science in their eyes.<br>
<br>
Therefore I would say that if Germany had won the war, we would have been substantially further behind the curve in both rocketry and nuclear than we are in the real world of 2003.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
You miss the main point of the A9/10 project... unlike the V2, it had one of the best guidance systems... a human pilot.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The winged A4 – the A9 – was intended to have a pilot in early development prototypes, but in the case of the final A9/A10, the hypersonic glider, this is far from clear. For one thing, any pilot sitting atop that thing might be able to guide it to NY, but he certainly would not be likely to see the Fatherland again. And the Germans, unlike the Japanese, were no more inclined towards kamikaze missions than Americans are. Furthermore, if there was a pilot plus all his life-support equipment, etc., there’s no lifting capacity left for any sort of bomb, never mind a massive early nuclear one.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I can see no appreciation in the remaining papers found on the A9/A10 of either the re-entry or supersonic flight problems the vehicle would face. Oh yes, re-entry is the right term. Just of the top of my head, the vehicle would reach a velocity of something like 6 or 7 thousand kph as it fell back into the atmosphere from an apogee of 300 kilometers. That would sufficiently damage any material they were likely to know about back in the 1940’s, quite apart from boiling the pilot, to ensure an early end to the mission. And if somehow that fate was avoided, the wings were required to avoid melting long enough to get this ship over the Atlantic. And this poor, recently boiled sucker… sorry, pilot, is supposed to steer it when there was no experience of supersonic--never mind hypersonic-- flight. Sorry, I don’t think this a viable project within a realistic time frame.<br>
<br>
BTW, the Sänger Orbital Bomber design project dates from the mid-1950, well after the end of WWII.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
As I have stated above, this is a hypothetical re-write of WWII, and as such I think it is safe to say that had the war gone differently for the Allies, and the Germans dominated Europe, unimpeded by Allied bombing of it's factories and research centers then the outcome is no longer certain. A tiny little historical change such as the development of a large 4 engine bomber would have given the German Luftwaffe the ability to strike the Soviet Union's factories which they had relocated beyond the reach of German 2 engine bomber's.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The Germans had large 4-engined strategic bombers planned in the 1930s, but these were scrubbed when the Luftwaffe (which was subordinate to the Wehrmacht and so seen as little more than a form of long range artillery) was ordered to concentrate on smaller aircraft better able to directly support the army. For the reasons stated above, I don’t see a victorious Germany ever starting to develop a strategic bomber in the early to mid 1940s.<br>
<br>
If fact, the US was fortunate to have the B-29 available to carry the Bomb. It was far beyond the capability of the B-17 and at one time it seemed the only bomber capable of lifting it would be the British Lancaster.<br>
<br>
The only nations with true strategic bomber fleets in WWII were the British and the Americans.<br>
<br>
