too many europeans dont give the US credit for saving europe. they would rather give russia credit...i think its because russia is no longer a superpower--anybody favors the underdog, for some reason. i dont think people would be so sympathetic of russia if it was still the soviet union. russia is very much a third world nation right now...developing, but still not on the economic level of most of europe, and much of asia. <br>
——————————————————————————————————<br>
<br>
But it WAS the Russians who &quot;saved&quot; most of Europe  (certainly all of eastern Europe) from the Nazis. Ask  any German what the central part of  WWII was  and he'll say &quot;the Eastern Front&quot; where up to 80% of their army were fighting the Russians. What was happening in the west was a sideshow to most Germans.<br>
<br>
(&quot;Saved&quot; is in quotes above because I'm not sure being saved by the Comminists from the Nazis is much of a &quot;save&quot;, but that's how it happened.)<br>
<br>
Only in western Europe was the saving done by the JOINT efforts of Britain and America. Even here it was a close-run thing in many instances. For example, only a swift thrust by the British to southern Denmark prevented it's &quot;liberation&quot; by the Red Army in the closing days of the war.<br>
<br>
Incidentally, much more of central/eastern Europe could have been save from the Russians if Roosevelt, who was not well by 1944 and shortly to die, had not ignored Churchill's advise and thought he could do a deal with Stalin. Just one result of this approach was probably the loss of Poland to the Communists. Stalin must have thought him a fool, but a &quot;useful&quot; one, from his point of view.<br>
<br>
And in the immediate post-war period, there was a civil war in Greece that the Communists very nearly won, while in Italy there very nearly was a Communist government voted in in the late 1940s. France too was in danger of a Communist electoral takeover for some years after the end of the war. Even in the western zones of Germany, there was a real risk of the Communists winning the first elections held about 1948, I think.<br>
<br>
What saved western Euroe from going Communist was (1) the Marshall Plan, (2) the formation of NATO, and (3) the RETURN of US forces in the late 1940's as the danger of Soviet expaansionism becaame clear, especially with the Berlin Airlift, which incidentally turned the population of the western zones of Germany from viewing the British and Americans as occupiers into seeing them as friends and allies.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/atom_anim.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 2203<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/8/03 3:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nazi Germany</span><hr size=1> I think that this thread has deviated from its original intent.  The topic is 'What if Germany had won WWII?', not 'How could Germany Win WWII?'  The idea is to explore an alternate history up to the present day... where would be technologically?  Would Germany and Japan become the world super powers and enter into a cold war?  Would that struggle lead to Germany expanding into manned space travel more rapidly than our history did?  <br>
